<div id=3D"outline-container-5" class=3D"outline-2">
<h2 id=3D"5">RFC: multifile ATD definition support via import statements</h=
2>
<div class=3D"outline-text-2" id=3D"text-5">
<p>
Archive: <a href=3D"https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/rfc-multifile-atd-definitio=
n-support-via-import-statements/17881/1">https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/rfc-mu=
ltifile-atd-definition-support-via-import-statements/17881/1</a>
</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-orgcc15fc9" class=3D"outline-3">
<h3 id=3D"orgcc15fc9">Martin Jambon announced</h3>
<div class=3D"outline-text-3" id=3D"text-orgcc15fc9">
<p>
Hello,
</p>

<p>
We're adding support for splitting <a href=3D"https://github.com/ahrefs/atd=
">ATD</a> type definitions into smaller files. It wasn't possible to  conve=
niently reference types defined from other ATD files until now, resulting i=
n large interface files (<a href=3D"https://github.com/semgrep/semgrep-inte=
rfaces/blob/main/semgrep_output_v1.atd">example</a>).
</p>

<p>
I would like a pair of eyes to help me check the sanity of the spec which i=
s copy-pasted below from the <a href=3D"https://github.com/ahrefs/atd/pull/=
451">pull request</a> before this goes live in atd 4.0.0.
</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-org9d64458" class=3D"outline-4">
<h4 id=3D"org9d64458">Import declarations</h4>
<div class=3D"outline-text-4" id=3D"text-org9d64458">
<p>
An ATD file may import other ATD modules using <code>import</code> declarat=
ions.
Import declarations must appear after any top-level annotations and before
any type definitions.
</p>

<p>
Syntax:
</p>
<blockquote>
<p>
import module.path &lt;annotations&gt; as alias &lt;annotations&gt;
</p>
</blockquote>

<p>
The <code>as</code> clause is optional. Without it, the local name of the i=
mported
module is the last component of the dotted path (e.g. <code>import foo.bar<=
/code>
binds the local name <code>bar</code>).
</p>

<p>
Type names from an imported module are referenced using dot notation:
<code>alias.typename</code> (or <code>lastcomponent.typename</code> when no=
 alias is given).
For example, if a module <code>types</code> is imported, the type <code>dat=
e</code> from
that module is written <code>types.date</code> in type expressions.
</p>

<p>
Annotations on the path or alias allow language-specific backends to
override the module name used in generated code. The annotation
<code>&lt;ocaml name=3D"..."&gt;</code> (or the equivalent for another targ=
et language)
on the path controls how the module is referenced in generated output,
while the same annotation on the <code>as</code> clause controls the local =
alias
name used in the generated code.
</p>

<p>
Examples:
</p>

<div class=3D"org-src-container">
<pre class=3D"src src-ocaml"><code><span style=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-styl=
e: italic;">(* </span><span style=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-style: italic;">S=
imple import: local name is "common"</span><span style=3D"color: #8f6f4a; f=
ont-style: italic;"> *)</span>
import mylib.common

<span style=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-style: italic;">(* </span><span style=
=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-style: italic;">Import with an alias</span><span s=
tyle=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-style: italic;"> *)</span>
import mylib.common <span style=3D"color: #006f00; font-weight: bold;">as</=
span> c

<span style=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-style: italic;">(* </span><span style=
=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-style: italic;">Using an imported type in a defini=
tion</span><span style=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-style: italic;"> *)</span>
<span style=3D"color: #242521; font-weight: bold;">type</span> <span style=
=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;">event</span> =3D {
  id : string;
  timestamp : common.date;
}
</code></pre>
</div>

<div class=3D"org-src-container">
<pre class=3D"src src-ocaml"><code><span style=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-styl=
e: italic;">(* </span><span style=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-style: italic;">L=
anguage-specific name annotation on the path</span><span style=3D"color: #8=
f6f4a; font-style: italic;"> *)</span>
import mylib.common &lt;ocaml name=3D<span style=3D"color: #ca3400;">"Mylib=
_common"</span>&gt;

<span style=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-style: italic;">(* </span><span style=
=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-style: italic;">Language-specific name annotation =
on the alias</span><span style=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-style: italic;"> *)<=
/span>
import mylib.common <span style=3D"color: #006f00; font-weight: bold;">as</=
span> c &lt;ocaml name=3D<span style=3D"color: #ca3400;">"Common"</span>&gt;
</code></pre>
</div>

<p>
Warning:
</p>
<blockquote>
<p>
Dotted module paths (e.g. <code>import foo.bar.baz</code>) are an experimen=
tal
feature. Each code generator maps them to file paths in its own way and
there is currently no guarantee of consistent behavior across backends.
When possible, prefer single-component module names (e.g. <code>import baz<=
/code>
or <code>import foo as bar</code>). Support for dotted module paths may be =
removed
in a future release.
</p>
</blockquote>
</div>
